    {"parentUuid":"8e58eb4d-c1c4-4480-81a2-1654b6129c86","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"1a2ac27d-e0ad-40eb-95a6-9746b540860d","agentId":"aa42e0168b719ed85","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UDi1UyeGfnVUSSK8JhHnWX","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"arXiv \"circuit complexity\" \"prime counting\" OR \"counting primes\" 2025 2026\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Rough numbers between consecutive primes - Terence Tao\",\"url\":\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2025/08/10/rough-numbers-between-consecutive-primes/\"},{\"title\":\"PRIMES: Research Papers\",\"url\":\"https://math.mit.edu/research/highschool/primes/papers.html\"},{\"title\":\"Computational Complexity Aug 2025\",\"url\":\"https://web3.arxiv.org/list/cs.CC/2025-08\"},{\"title\":\"[1302.6245] Quantum Computation of Prime Number Functions\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1302.6245\"},{\"title\":\"[1504.05240] On the complexity of computing prime tables\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1504.05240\"},{\"title\":\"Computational Complexity Feb 2026\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/list/cs.CC/current\"},{\"title\":\"The Top 10 Math Discoveries of 2025 | Scientific American\",\"url\":\"https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/the-top-10-math-discoveries-of-2025/\"},{\"title\":\"Computational Complexity Mar 2025\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/list/cs.CC/2025-03?skip=0&show=25\"},{\"title\":\"[2407.05651] Primes in almost all short intervals\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.05651\"},{\"title\":\"arXiv:2308.03126v2 [math.NT] 9 Aug 2023 BULLETIN (New Series) OF THE\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2308.03126\"}]\n\nBased on the web search results, I found some relevant information about circuit complexity and primes, though the specific combination you requested didn't yield many direct matches:\n\n## Findings:\n\n**Circuit Complexity and Counting (2025-2026):**\n\nResearch on constant-depth circuits with MOD_m gates shows that when m is prime, computational ability is limited in small size, yet composite m unlocks rich capabilities, with work extending results for computing symmetric functions in CC^0.\n\n**Prime-Related arXiv Papers (2025-2026):**\n\n- There is a March 2025 arXiv paper titled \"Primes via Zeros: Interactive Proofs for Testing Primality of Natural Classes of Ideals\"\n\n- A paper (arXiv:2407.05651) sharpens results about prime distribution, showing that the interval [n, n+n^(1/21.5+ε)] contains prime numbers for almost all n\n\n**Related Work:**\n\nThere is quantum circuit work proposing a quantum circuit that creates a superposition of all prime numbers less than 2^n, which can be combined with the quantum Fourier transform to yield an estimate of the prime counting function, though this paper is from 2013, predating your specified timeframe.\n\nThe search results indicate that while there are papers on circuit complexity and separately on prime-related mathematics from 2025-2026, I did not find papers specifically addressing both \"circuit complexity\" and \"prime counting\" together in recent arXiv submissions.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"6d3e6e6e-6515-4307-a40d-29815c4b4cbb","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:07:24.820Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8e58eb4d-c1c4-4480-81a2-1654b6129c86","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"56eefe41-e662-4b21-a5bb-cc1c276017d2","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wise-snacking-rose"}
    {"parentUuid":"eea9bb82-052d-456b-97de-b3ddde2806cc","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"1a2ac27d-e0ad-40eb-95a6-9746b540860d","agentId":"aa42e0168b719ed85","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ko4yyKDdiJ6H9dA7mZtRiQ","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"arXiv \"nonlinear sieve\" OR \"quadratic sieve\" prime counting 2025 2026\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Quadratic sieve - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_sieve\"},{\"title\":\"An Overview of the Sieve Method and its History\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0505521\"},{\"title\":\"arXiv:2404.04239v2 [math.NT] 8 Jan 2025\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2404.04239\"},{\"title\":\"Quadratic Sieve -- from Wolfram MathWorld\",\"url\":\"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/QuadraticSieve.html\"},{\"title\":\"A Constructive Heuristic Sieve for the Twin Prime Problem Yuhang Shi\",\"url\":\"https://www.arxiv.org/pdf/2507.03107\"},{\"title\":\"an empirical comparison of the quadratic sieve factoring ...\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2111.02967\"},{\"title\":\"Prime Number Sieving—A Systematic Review with Performance Analysis\",\"url\":\"https://www.mdpi.com/1999-4893/17/4/157\"},{\"title\":\"1 A Beginner’s Guide To The General Number Field Sieve Michael Case\",\"url\":\"https://www.cs.umd.edu/~gasarch/TOPICS/factoring/NFSmadeeasy.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Algebra & Number Theory Volume 19 2025 No. 1 msp\",\"url\":\"https://msp.org/ant/2025/19-1/ant-v19-n1-s.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"[2602.20917] Primes in arithmetic progressions to large moduli and refinements of Harman's sieve\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.20917\"}]\n\nBased on the web search results, here's what I found regarding arXiv papers on \"nonlinear sieve\" and \"quadratic sieve\" related to prime counting from 2025-2026:\n\n## Recent arXiv Papers on Sieve Methods (2025-2026)\n\n**Recent developments in sieve theory for prime counting:**\n\nA modification of the linear sieve with strong factorization properties has been introduced that equidistributes primes up to size x in arithmetic progressions to moduli up to x^(10/17), surpassing the previous level of distribution x^(4/7) with standard linear sieve weights.\n\nThis approach provides a new upper bound on the count of twin primes.\n\n**Additional 2026 paper on prime distribution:**\n\nA February 2026 arXiv paper studies the average distribution of primes of size x in arithmetic progressions to moduli larger than x^(1/2), obtaining mean value theorems for primes with bilinear forms of moduli up to x^(9/17) or with trilinear forms of moduli up to x^(17/32).\n\nThe search results also include references to historical quadratic sieve work, including a 2025 RSA-150 factorization record (150-digit number) achieved using the quadratic sieve, though this focuses on factorization rather than prime counting per se.\n\nThese represent recent advances in sieve-theoretic approaches to understanding prime distributions, though I should note that the specific term \"nonlinear sieve\" may not be standard terminology in recent literature.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9fbeaae8-3501-446f-901c-b562b5dac5bb","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:07:25.859Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"eea9bb82-052d-456b-97de-b3ddde2806cc","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"56eefe41-e662-4b21-a5bb-cc1c276017d2","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wise-snacking-rose"}
    {"parentUuid":"cf09e6e2-5b8c-4161-a57d-839a9a31baad","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"1a2ac27d-e0ad-40eb-95a6-9746b540860d","agentId":"aa42e0168b719ed85","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01A7ctmUjCNJEgo8T6A3gdSg","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"arXiv BPSW primality test 2025 new results verification\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"arXiv:2505.00730v1 [cs.SC] 28 Apr 2025\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.00730\"},{\"title\":\"STRENGTHENING THE BAILLIE-PSW PRIMALITY TEST\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2006.14425\"},{\"title\":\"TAXONOMY AND PRACTICAL EVALUATION OF PRIMALITY TESTING ALGORITHMS\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2006.08444\"},{\"title\":\"Primality Testing: Baillie-PSW | Brandon G. Nguyen\",\"url\":\"https://brandon.nguyen.vc/notes/cryptography/baillie-psw/\"},{\"title\":\"Baillie–PSW primality test - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BPSW_primality_test\"},{\"title\":\"PPT : New Low Complexity Deterministic Primality\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1908.06964\"},{\"title\":\"The Baillie-PSW primality test Thomas R. Nicely\",\"url\":\"https://faculty.lynchburg.edu/~nicely/misc/bpsw.html\"},{\"title\":\"[2006.08444] Taxonomy and Practical Evaluation of Primality Testing Algorithms\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.08444\"},{\"title\":\"[2006.14425] Strengthening the Baillie-PSW primality test\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2006.14425\"},{\"title\":\"AKS primality test - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AKS_primality_test\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found regarding arXiv papers on BPSW primality testing and recent results:\n\n## Key Findings\n\n**Recent arXiv Papers on BPSW and Primality Testing:**\n\nThe most directly relevant paper is \"Strengthening the Baillie-PSW Primality Test\" by Robert Baillie and colleagues (arXiv:2006.14425), though this is from 2020 rather than 2025.\n\nThis paper describes a significant strengthening of the BPSW test that comes at almost no additional computational cost by including what they call Lucas-V pseudoprimes, of which there are only five less than 10^15.\n\n**2025 Primality Testing Research:**\n\nThere is a more recent 2025 paper (arXiv:2505.00730) that discusses primality testing algorithms, though it focuses on a different approach. It leverages Galois theory for deterministic primality testing using a circulant matrix approach, which unlike probabilistic methods like Miller–Rabin, provides fully deterministic results.\n\n**Historical Context on BPSW:**\n\nNo composite number below 2^64 (approximately 1.845·10^19) passes the strong or standard Baillie–PSW test, making this test a deterministic primality test on numbers below that bound. There are also no known composite numbers above that bound that pass the test.\n\nIf you're looking for specific 2025 verification results on BPSW pseudoprimes, the search results don't show any new counterexamples or major breakthroughs in that area published on arXiv in 2025.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"a47d94a7-40f1-4ca4-a7f6-31a0179cf611","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:07:27.642Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"cf09e6e2-5b8c-4161-a57d-839a9a31baad","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"56eefe41-e662-4b21-a5bb-cc1c276017d2","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wise-snacking-rose"}
    {"parentUuid":"83500265-db73-45dc-8a90-fc354f50f825","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"1a2ac27d-e0ad-40eb-95a6-9746b540860d","agentId":"aa42e0168b719ed85","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017b7vUC9sty98p5GkC1pQmp","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Chiari \"bounded arithmetic\" primality TC0 2025 arXiv\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2504.17041] Feasibility of Primality in Bounded Arithmetic\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.17041\"},{\"title\":\"ON THE REALIZABILITY OF PRIME CONJECTURES IN HEYTING ARITHMETIC Milan Rosko\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.07774\"},{\"title\":\"Open induction in a bounded arithmetic for TC0 | Archive for Mathematical Logic | Springer Nature Link\",\"url\":\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00153-014-0414-7\"},{\"title\":\"[2309.00425] On primes in arithmetic progressions and bounded gaps between many primes\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.00425\"},{\"title\":\"[2506.03005] Multi-scale representation of integer sets: application to prime numbers\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.03005\"},{\"title\":\"November | 2025 | What's new - Terence Tao\",\"url\":\"https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2025/11/\"},{\"title\":\"Remarks on AKS Primality Testing Algorithm and A Flaw in the Deﬁnition of P\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1402.0146\"},{\"title\":\"On bounded arithmetic augmented by the ability to count certain sets of primes\",\"url\":\"https://projecteuclid.org/journals/journal-of-symbolic-logic/volume-74/issue-2/On-bounded-arithmetic-augmented-by-the-ability-to-count-certain/10.2178/jsl/1243948322.short\"},{\"title\":\"Number Theory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/list/math.NT/recent\"},{\"title\":\"[2304.02770] Tight Correlation Bounds for Circuits Between AC0 and TC0\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.02770\"}]\n\nThe search found a highly relevant paper. Here's what I found:\n\n## Key Result\n\nThe paper proves the correctness of the AKS algorithm within the bounded arithmetic theory T²_count or, equivalently, the first-order consequences of the theory VTC⁰ expanded by the smash function, denoted VTC⁰₂.\n\n## Research Approach\n\nThe approach initially demonstrates the correctness within the theory S¹₂ + iWPHP augmented by two algebraic axioms and then shows that they are provable in VTC⁰₂. The two axioms are: a generalized version of Fermat's Little Theorem and an axiom adding a new function symbol which injectively maps roots of polynomials over a definable finite field to numbers bounded by the degree of the given polynomial.\n\n## Additional Formalizations\n\nThe paper provides new formalizations of parts of number theory and algebra: in PV₁, they formalize Legendre's Formula on the prime factorization of n!, key properties of the Combinatorial Number System and the existence of cyclotomic polynomials over the finite fields ℤ/p.\n\nThe paper is available on arXiv as reference [2504.17041], dated April 23, 2025 (with a revised version from January 27, 2026), and is authored by Raheleh Jalali and co-authors.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"ca3ab1f0-f74e-40cc-b2ff-ecb1c6ff8d9a","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:07:27.960Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"83500265-db73-45dc-8a90-fc354f50f825","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"56eefe41-e662-4b21-a5bb-cc1c276017d2","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wise-snacking-rose"}
