    {"parentUuid":"ec84ac5a-74cd-477d-a4a5-a1995bb3a5b2","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"af1e03c2beb85aa02","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Fv4ySXMfSLUbYEmU6ovugA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Y5YEgnph748fAk5c1jA5UQ","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/experiments/circuit_complexity/lucy_dp_structure.py"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5085,"cache_read_input_tokens":12087,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5085,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CZjBAs4fYLUv3GtE3P1Fs","type":"assistant","uuid":"4c672921-7ac7-4fde-ae02-3563d4ac9987","timestamp":"2026-04-04T18:07:04.297Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"56eefe41-e662-4b21-a5bb-cc1c276017d2","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wise-snacking-rose"}
    {"parentUuid":"4c672921-7ac7-4fde-ae02-3563d4ac9987","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"1a2ac27d-e0ad-40eb-95a6-9746b540860d","agentId":"af1e03c2beb85aa02","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Y5YEgnph748fAk5c1jA5UQ","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\"\"\"\n2\tLucy DP Floor-Value Mapping Structure Analysis\n3\tSession 12 - April 2026\n4\t\n5\tKey insight being investigated:\n6\tThe Lucy DP computes pi(x) by iteratively sieving over primes p = 2, 3, 5, ...\n7\tAt each step, it updates S(v) for all v in the floor-value set V = {floor(x/k)}.\n8\t\n9\tThe update at prime p is:\n10\t  S(v, p) = S(v, p-1) - [S(floor(v/p), p-1) - S(p-1, p-1)]\n11\t\n12\tThis means the mapping v -> floor(v/p) is a FUNCTION from V to V (with merging).\n13\tWe investigate the ALGEBRAIC STRUCTURE of these mappings:\n14\t1. How many distinct mappings occur?\n15\t2. What is the graph structure of the mapping v -> floor(v/p)?\n16\t3. Can the composition of all mappings be computed in O(1) depth?\n17\t4. Does the mapping have \"parallel prefix\" structure?\n18\t\n19\tIf the composition of mappings has low circuit complexity, this could\n20\tlead to a TC^0 or NC^1 algorithm for pi(x).\n21\t\"\"\"\n22\t\n23\timport math\n24\tfrom collections import defaultdict, Counter\n25\timport sympy\n26\t\n27\tdef get_floor_values(x):\n28\t    \"\"\"Get all distinct values of floor(x/k) for k = 1, ..., x.\"\"\"\n29\t    vals = set()\n30\t    k = 1\n31\t    while k * k <= x:\n32\t        vals.add(x // k)\n33\t        vals.add(k)\n34\t        k += 1\n35\t    return sorted(vals)\n36\t\n37\tdef lucy_dp(x):\n38\t    \"\"\"Standard Lucy DP for pi(x), instrumented to track mappings.\"\"\"\n39\t    sqrtx = int(math.isqrt(x))\n40\t\n41\t    # S[v] = number of integers in [2, v] not sieved by primes <= current prime\n42\t    # Initially S[v] = v - 1\n43\t    S = {}\n44\t    V = get_floor_values(x)\n45\t\n46\t    for v in V:\n47\t        S[v] = v - 1\n48\t\n49\t    mappings = []  # Track (prime, mapping_graph)\n50\t\n51\t    for p in range(2, sqrtx + 1):\n52\t        if S[p] > S[p - 1]:  # p is prime\n53\t            # Record the mapping: which v values get updated, and what floor(v/p) maps to\n54\t            mapping = {}\n55\t            updates = 0\n56\t            for v in reversed(V):\n57\t                if v < p * p:\n58\t                    break\n59\t                vp = v // p\n60\t                mapping[v] = vp\n61\t                S[v] -= S[vp] - S[p - 1]\n62\t                updates += 1\n63\t\n64\t            mappings.append((p, mapping, updates))\n65\t\n66\t    return S[x], mappings\n67\t\n68\tdef analyze_mapping_structure(x):\n69\t    \"\"\"Analyze the structure of floor-value mappings in Lucy DP.\"\"\"\n70\t    pi_x, mappings = lucy_dp(x)\n71\t    V = get_floor_values(x)\n72\t\n73\t    print(f\"=== Lucy DP Structure Analysis for x = {x} ===\")\n74\t    print(f\"pi({x}) = {pi_x}\")\n75\t    print(f\"|V| = {len(V)} floor-values\")\n76\t    print(f\"Number of prime steps: {len(mappings)}\")\n77\t    print()\n78\t\n79\t    # Analyze each mapping\n80\t    print(\"--- Per-prime mapping analysis ---\")\n81\t    total_updates = 0\n82\t    for p, mapping, updates in mappings:\n83\t        # Is the mapping injective on the affected values?\n84\t        targets = list(mapping.values())\n85\t        unique_targets = len(set(targets))\n86\t        injective = (unique_targets == len(targets))\n87\t\n88\t        # What fraction of V is affected?\n89\t        frac_affected = updates / len(V)\n90\t\n91\t        total_updates += updates\n92\t\n93\t        print(f\"  p={p}: {updates}/{len(V)} values updated ({frac_affected:.1%}), \"\n94\t              f\"injective={injective}, unique_targets={unique_targets}\")\n95\t\n96\t    print(f\"\\nTotal updates across all primes: {total_updates}\")\n97\t    print(f\"Average updates per prime: {total_updates / len(mappings):.1f}\")\n98\t\n99\t    # Key question: can we compose all mappings?\n100\t    # The DP is: S_final = f_last ∘ ... ∘ f_2 (S_initial)\n101\t    # where each f_p is an AFFINE transformation on the S vector\n102\t    # f_p: S[v] -> S[v] - S[floor(v/p)] + S[p-1] for v >= p^2\n103\t\n104\t    # Represent as matrix: S_new = A_p * S_old + b_p\n105\t    # A_p = I - Delta_p where Delta_p has entry (v, floor(v/p)) = 1 for v >= p^2\n106\t    # b_p has entry S[p-1] for v >= p^2 (but this depends on current S!)\n107\t\n108\t    # Wait - the b_p term depends on S[p-1] which changes at each step!\n109\t    # S[p-1] after processing primes up to p-1 is actually pi(p-1).\n110\t    # And pi(p-1) = p-1 - 1 if p is the first prime, or depends on prior steps.\n111\t    # Actually S[p-1] at the point where we process prime p equals pi(p-1)\n112\t    # since p-1 < p^2 and thus S[p-1] is never modified after we finish primes < p.\n113\t\n114\t    # So b_p[v] = pi(p-1) for v >= p^2, which is a KNOWN value at step p.\n115\t    # Therefore the transformation IS affine: S_new = A_p * S + b_p\n116\t\n117\t    # The composition of affine transforms:\n118\t    # f_last ∘ ... ∘ f_2 is also affine: S_final = M * S_initial + c\n119\t    # where M = A_last * ... * A_2 and c accumulates the affine terms\n120\t\n121\t    # The matrix M is the product of O(pi(sqrt(x))) matrices, each of dimension |V| x |V|\n122\t    # This is the IMP (iterated matrix product) problem!\n123\t\n124\t    # Key question: do these matrices have SPECIAL structure that makes\n125\t    # their product easier to compute?\n126\t\n127\t    # Each A_p = I - E_p where E_p is a very sparse matrix\n128\t    # (I - E_last) * ... * (I - E_2)\n129\t    # = I - sum E_p + sum_{p<q} E_p*E_q - ...\n130\t    # This is inclusion-exclusion! And it has 2^{pi(sqrt(x))} terms.\n131\t\n132\t    # BUT: the E_p matrices might commute or have other structure.\n133\t    # E_p has entry (v, floor(v/p)) = 1 for v >= p^2\n134\t    # E_q has entry (v, floor(v/q)) = 1 for v >= q^2\n135\t\n136\t    # E_p * E_q has entry (v, floor(floor(v/p)/