    x=1000, pi(x)=168, F_5: min dimension d=4, N=10
    x=1000, pi(x)=168, F_7: min dimension d=3, N=10
    
    ======================================================================
    Hypersurface point counting approach
    ======================================================================
    Hypersurface approach: constructing f_x requires knowing pi(x).
    Over F_q: Chevalley-Warning gives congruences #{V} ≡ 0 (mod q)
    when deg < dim. This constrains but doesn't determine #{V}.
    
    The fundamental issue: the COEFFICIENTS of f_x encode pi(x),
    so computing them is as hard as computing pi(x) itself.
    
    Congruence structure of pi(x):
      pi(x) mod 2 for x=2..1000: {0: 522, 1: 477}
      pi(x) mod 3 for x=2..1000: {0: 348, 1: 347, 2: 304}
      pi(x) mod 5 for x=2..1000: {0: 182, 1: 229, 2: 224, 3: 162, 4: 202}
